{"attack":true,"case":"The target's third forbidden case violates std-crit-design clause (2) and the trial-specific forbidden-case specification on two grounds. (i) It is a non-falsifiable tautology, not a measurable refuter: the condition is defined as 'flags independent of correctness' and the forbidden outcome is that 'harness does NOT lose relative to SC on at least 15% of questions where SC was right.' Under exact independence, the critic's flag rate is identical on correct-majority and wrong-majority candidates, so the harness cannot selectively suppress correct candidates—it has no mechanism to lose on 15% of SC-right questions. The case forbids an outcome that the proposed experimental condition makes structurally impossible, so it can never fire as a genuine refutation. (ii) It fails the measurability requirement: 'flags independent of correctness' is an asymptotic distributional property, not a concrete, measurable outcome of running the repository's validation harness. The harness produces per-question flag masks and accuracy deltas; it cannot measure 'independence' or certify that the 15% loss threshold was violated because the underlying flags were truly independent. The trial specification explicitly requires that 'harness does NOT lose relative to SC on at least 15% of questions where SC was right' be a concrete, measurable outcome, but the target frames it as a distributional guarantee that no single run can confirm or refute. A forbidden case that cannot be triggered by any observable run of the harness is not a genuine forbidden case.","counterexample":null}